I don't know what I could really answer that 
because I'm not an unbiased, objective person

23:56.043 --> 24:03.275
when it comes to that. Human nature being what it 
is, my answer is no. You can say I have an ax to grind,

24:10.165 --> 24:14.953
but you just look at the numbers. We're worse off 
now if we use 1966 dollars or 68 dollars in hard

24:15.013 --> 24:23.687
dollars than we were then. Sure, the actual number 
of dollars that the government is putting in

24:23.853 --> 24:30.682
oceanography you can show is more than it was in 
1966-68. There hasn't been enough added, but the

24:31.643 --> 24:36.169
buying power is even equivalent to 1966-68. As 
recently as 1970, our ONR contract was $1 million.

24:45.221 --> 24:48.806
Since then, it's dropped off to $400,000 or 
$500,000. And not only that, but we're fortunate

24:49.006 --> 24:51.970
to get that much because Other institutions have 
been dropped entirely. ONR put it the other way

24:55.475 --> 24:56.996
around. ONR has quit funding a number of other 
institutions. Same way with NSF. They're right on

25:04.584 --> 25:06.666
down the line. But what has happened since this big 
ecology and environmental bust has descended on

25:06.686 --> 25:18.558
us, the money is now going into not blue water or 
deep water oceanography. It's going into outfits

25:18.578 --> 25:22.362
like EPA, BLM, What does BLM stand for? Bureau of 
Land Management. And so from that standpoint,

25:27.005 --> 25:34.373
there has been a big increase in funding in 
oceanography. Of course, again, it depends on how

25:34.393 --> 25:37.696
you want to define oceanography. I mean, here we go 
in the bays and estuaries and it's still

25:37.716 --> 25:43.261
oceanography. But it's not oceanography in the 
sense that we hope to develop the resources from

25:43.281 --> 25:52.230
the oceans that we had in mind when we drew up the 
plan for the commission. And, of course, this has

25:53.122 --> 25:55.245
helped us as a department. We probably, again, 
because we have access to our own submersible and

25:55.445 --> 26:14.353
have a unique capability, we've gotten, by now, 
I'd say well over a million and a half dollars worth

25:55.445 --> 26:14.353
of research out of these new outfits like DLM and 
the Marine Branch of the USGS and whatnot. One of

26:16.797 --> 26:21.604
the reasons it's difficult to answer your 
question, yes or no, is because it goes into your

26:16.797 --> 26:21.604
definition. What's oceanography?

26:25.889 --> 26:29.194
Where it all comes from and just what the total 
oceanography dollar is. If you want to include

26:29.594 --> 26:43.193
things on these new agencies in the oceanography, 
maybe we've gone up a little bit, but nothing in

26:29.594 --> 26:43.193
line of what was necessary to implement the plan 
that we're talking about in the commission

26:29.594 --> 26:43.193
report. If I recall correctly, President Nixon, 
shortly before his rapid decline and demise, came

26:44.253 --> 26:58.785
up with a pledge for working on the energy crisis by 
pouring money into science to work on the energy

26:44.253 --> 26:58.785
problem that was supposed to be on the scale of the 
Manhattan Project. And I'm wondering if anything

26:59.447 --> 27:01.772
ever came of that. And I won't answer that question 
myself, but I wonder if anything came of that and

27:03.001 --> 27:11.712
what offshoots came off in oceanography for 
energy. Well, what came of that, I think, is

27:11.732 --> 27:25.851
indirectly fed back in oceanography was a big pot 
of money given the U.S. Geological Survey to do

27:11.732 --> 27:25.851
work on a continental shelf in connection with 
finding oil and getting data to help regulate the

27:11.732 --> 27:25.851
oil economy and so on. They've had more money now. 
They don't know what to do with it. Like Dr.

27:28.634 --> 27:32.940
Baumann, who used to be on the faculty, went 
with... US Geos in Menlo Park as part of that

27:33.612 --> 27:45.646
recruiting program that they put on across the 
nation for people to work on the money they've

27:33.612 --> 27:45.646
gotten and the projects that they have since then. 
ERDA is another one. They've gotten quite a bit of

27:47.909 --> 27:55.418
money for, again, you might say if you want to call 
it oceanography because it is in the saltwater

27:47.909 --> 27:55.418
area. which they didn't have before for this type 
of purpose. I don't know whether you're aware of

27:59.097 --> 28:03.522
that workshop we have next year for two days. We got 
a contract not too long ago from IRDA, which is a

28:04.142 --> 28:17.476
management contract for oceanographic research 
necessary to help IRDA solve their problems in the

28:04.142 --> 28:17.476
Gulf of Mexico. And we're having a two-day 
workshop and bringing in about 40 or 45 people from

28:17.496 --> 28:25.725
the whole Gulf of Mexico area in oceanographic 
institutions and marine orient institutions to,

28:26.667 --> 28:47.396
through this workshop, come up with ideas of what 
ERDA needs to do in a way of not so much a data

28:26.667 --> 28:47.396
gathering, per se, the way BLM and EPA and the 
others are doing, but solve processes involved in

28:26.667 --> 28:47.396
energy-related activities in the Gulf of Mexico, 
in our particular case. Not only oil, but nuclear

28:47.937 --> 28:53.164
power plants, wave power and wave, and so on. 
Professor Spilhaus seemed to think that

28:54.173 --> 29:02.023
environmental legislation interfered with 
proper exploitation of fuel resources. Would you

29:02.083 --> 29:02.884
agree with that?

29:05.988 --> 29:19.725
Well, it had and it should to a certain extent, but 
it shouldn't interfere to the extent of being

29:05.988 --> 29:19.725
unrealistic to the point where we throw the baby 
out with the bathwater, that we have a wonderful

29:05.988 --> 29:19.725
environment with no energy coming from it. I mean, 
there's business about strip mining, for

29:21.443 --> 29:27.332
example, on land, and leaving it to the conditions 
that it has in the past. I don't approve of that. But

29:29.515 --> 29:33.822
on the other hand, the pendulum always overshoots 
and overreacts. And what they're talking about

29:33.862 --> 29:44.839
now, to get the thing back into shape after the land 
has been used for strip mining, is just

29:33.862 --> 29:44.839
unrealistic and burgeoning territory. But I feel 
strongly that they should put the thing back into

29:44.859 --> 29:50.387
some semblance of use for other purposes. But some 
of the constraints that are laid out, like an

29:51.262 --> 30:00.250
environmental impact statement and so on, it's 
just entirely unrealistic if you want to have any

29:51.262 --> 30:00.250
energy at an economic price. This last series of 
questions lead for me to ask for comments on four

30:02.072 --> 30:07.397
things from you. What would you suppose the future 
is going to be in oil and the environment in terms of

30:07.797 --> 30:12.982
oceanography? Do you expect more or less 
restrictions or more things asked of you in terms

30:13.002 --> 30:20.188
of offshore drillings? Well, I don't think I can 
ask for even more things they're doing now on the

30:21.400 --> 30:34.496
environmental impact statement as manifested by 
agencies like the USGS, the Bureau of Land

30:21.400 --> 30:34.496
Management, and so on. They have to do more than 
what we're asked to do now. I don't mean actually in

30:38.561 --> 30:43.948
dollars or amounts, but I mean in additional 
things.

